PART ONE — CONCEPT NOTE
1.1  Background and Rationale
The global professional landscape is evolving faster than at any point in history. Accelerating technological change, the rise of the green economy, digital transformation, artificial intelligence, and shifting geopolitical dynamics are creating an entirely new set of demands on the next generation of professionals. Yet, the majority of young people, particularly across Africa and the Global South, continue to navigate these shifts without structured guidance, mentorship, or access to the networks that unlock opportunity.
The original SLEDGE Mentorship Program was established as a focused six-week initiative for early-career professionals in the energy and sustainability space. Over successive cohorts, a clear pattern emerged: participants arrived not just with questions about the energy sector, but with deeper questions about professional identity, career architecture, and their place in a rapidly shifting global ecosystem. The demand for a broader, more structurally ambitious programme became impossible to ignore.
This concept note presents the expanded SLEDGE 10-Week Mentorship Program, a programme that retains its founding commitment to empowering emerging talent, while broadening its scope to serve ambitious professionals across multiple fields and specialisations.
1.2  The Problem We Are Solving
Three interconnected challenges continue to limit the potential of young professionals globally:
Career disorientation: Many talented individuals lack clarity on where to focus, what skills to prioritise, and how to build a coherent professional trajectory.
Mentorship inequality: Access to quality mentorship remains concentrated among those who already have networks, institutional affiliations, or economic privilege.
Skills-to-opportunity mismatch: Even technically skilled graduates frequently lack the professional awareness, strategic thinking, and personal branding necessary to convert ability into impact.

SLEDGE exists to systematically address all three challenges — not through one-off advice, but through a structured, community-driven, multi-week learning experience.
1.3  Program Vision and Mission
Vision:  To become the most influential professional mentorship ecosystem for emerging talent across Africa and beyond, a network that consistently produces purposeful, globally competitive leaders.
Mission:  To equip participants with the clarity, skills, networks, and confidence needed to navigate the global professional ecosystem and build careers of lasting impact.
