PART THREE — CAPSTONE GROUP PROJECT

3.1  Purpose and Philosophy
The Capstone Group Project is the defining deliverable of the SLEDGE 10-Week Programme. It is not a classroom exercise. It is a real piece of work — a proposal, a plan, an analysis, a campaign, or a prototype — that participants could genuinely take beyond the programme into the world.

The Capstone is designed to achieve four things simultaneously:
Integrate learning across all ten weeks into a coherent, applied output.
Build experience of collaborative, cross-functional professional work.
Develop participants' confidence in presenting and defending ideas to an audience.
Produce something of tangible value — to participants, to organisations, and potentially to the world.

3.2  Team Structure
Teams of 3–5 participants. Cross-track teams are encouraged — a project combining energy, communications, and policy perspectives will be stronger than a single-track team.
Each team nominates a Project Lead responsible for coordination and final submission.
Teams are formed in Week 3 and begin scoping their project from Week 4 onward.

3.3  Project Options
Teams choose one of the following project formats. The chosen format must be appropriate to their topic and sector.

Format
Description
Example
Policy Brief
A structured analysis and recommendation document targeting a specific policy problem.
Youth employment in the clean energy sector in Nigeria
Business Concept
A lean business plan or startup concept with market analysis, value proposition, and financial outline.
A platform connecting African engineers to green infrastructure projects
Research Report
An evidence-based analysis of a professional or sectoral challenge, with conclusions and recommendations.
Barriers to women's leadership in African tech companies
Campaign Proposal
A communications or advocacy campaign with clear objectives, audience, messaging, and channels.
A social media campaign to drive youth participation in climate policy
Career Toolkit
A practical resource designed to help a specific professional audience navigate a real challenge.
A guide for African graduates entering international development organisations


